{{Infobox organization |name = Australian Watercolour Institute |image = |image_border = |size = <!-- default 200 --> |alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> |caption = |map = <!-- optional --> |msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px --> |malt = <!-- map alt text --> |mcaption = <!-- optional --> |abbreviation = AWI |motto = |formation = 1923 |extinction = <!-- date of extinction, optional --> |type = Non-profit |status = |purpose = Visual arts |headquarters = Sydney, Australia |location = |coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> |region_served = Australia |membership = By invitation |language = English |leader_title = President |leader_name = David van Nunen |main_organ = Committee |parent_organization = <!-- if one --> |affiliations = <!-- if any --> |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = http://www.awi.com.au/ |remarks = }}
The '''Australian Watercolour Institute''' (AWI) is a non-profit membership organization devoted to the advancement of [[watercolour painting]] in [[Australia]]. It was founded in 1923 by six painters in [[Sydney]], and was modeled after the [[Royal Watercolour Society]] and the [[American Watercolor Society]].
==History== The AWI's first exhibition occurred in 1924. A students' exhibition began in 1930. Until 1974, the AWI met in a variety of places and the annual exhibitions were held in different galleries. In that year, it received a grant enabling the AWI to rent space in a building on Sydney's Sussex Street. A reciprocal exhibition with the American Watercolor Society occurred in 1975, and in 1977, an AWI exhibition toured New Zealand. The international presence expanded to include Mexico City, Mexico; Spain; Vancouver, Canada; Hong Kong; and Korea (4th Asian Grand Watercolour Festival, Busan Biennale).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awi.com.au/AWI%20HISTORY%201..htm |title=AWI History |work=awi.com.au |accessdate=21 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003084821/http://www.awi.com.au/AWI%20HISTORY%201..htm |archivedate=3 October 2009 |df= }}</ref>
The founding members were J. Bennett, [[Alfred James Daplyn]], [[Albert Henry Fullwood]], [[Benjamin Edwin Minns]], [[Martin Stainforth]] and Charles Ephraim Smith Tindall. Invited foundation members included [[Albert Collins (painter)|Albert Collins]], John Eldershaw, [[Hans Heysen]], [[Norman Lindsay]], [[Sydney Long]], [[Arthur Streeton]], John D Moore, [[J. W. Tristram]] and [[Blamire Young]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/media/index.php?id=283 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-10-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919083127/http://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/media/index.php?id=283 |archivedate=2009-09-19 }}</ref> Past presidents include [[George Duncan (painter)|George Duncan]] and [[Hal Missingham]]. Other notable members include [[Ronald Steuart]], winner of the 1958 [[Wynne Prize]], and [[Robert Wade (watercolor artist)|Robert Wade]], winner of the 1986 "Advance Australia Medal" for outstanding contribution to Australian watercolour.<ref name="FeaturedArtists">{{cite web|url=http://www.watlingart.com/artists_information.php?ID=8 |title=Featured Artists |work=watlingart.com |accessdate=21 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605235055/http://www.watlingart.com/artists_information.php?ID=8 |archivedate=5 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> While membership was by invitation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsconnect.com.au/troupes/australianwatercolourinstitute.htm |title=Australian Watercolour Institute - AWI |work=artsconnect.com.au |accessdate=20 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007102843/http://www.artsconnect.com.au/troupes/australianwatercolourinstitute.htm |archivedate=7 October 2009 |df= }}</ref> it was not a requirement for exhibiting at the annual exhibition, such as the example of Heysen.<ref name="HansHeysen">{{cite book|last=Hylton|first=Jane |author2=John Neylon|title=Hans Heysen: Into the Light |publisher=Wakefield Press|year=2005 |series=Carrick Hill series|pages=17|isbn=1-86254-657-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xTfexysnFAIC&pg=PA17&dq=%22Australian+Watercolour+Institute%22&hl=en&ei=e2imS-_IIYrAsgP1-aS9BA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Australian%20Watercolour%20Institute%22&f=false}}</ref> [[Jean Isherwood]]'s first exhibited work with the AWI. in 1934. was a small painting, but thereafter, she became a frequent exhibitor in major art exhibitions. In 2006, ten percent of the membership were recipients of honours awarded by the Australian state ([[Orders, decorations, and medals of Australia|Australia Honours]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/media/index.php?id=102 |title=Australia's eminent watercolourists launch their major anniversary exhibition & book |date=23 November 2006 |work=mosman.nsw.gov.au |accessdate=21 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919062926/http://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/media/index.php?id=102 |archivedate=19 September 2009 |df= }}</ref>
==Publications== AWI published its first book, ''Australian Watercolour Institute: 75th anniversary 1923-1998'' on the occasion of its 75th anniversary in 1998. Its second book, ''The Australian Watercolour Institute: A Galley of Australia's Finest Watercolours'', was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosman.nsw.gov.au/events/1368/AWI-85th-annual-exhibition|title=Australian Watercolour Institute 85th Anniversary Exhibition|work=mosman.nsw.gov.au|accessdate=20 March 2010}}</ref> The 2006 edition reproduces over 150 contemporary Australian watercolour works, as well as forty historical ones, and includes essays that document Australia's watercolouring history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bunbury.wa.gov.au/library/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=125E7533Q9031.73900&profile=bun&uri=link=3100012~!108692~!3100001~!3100002&aspect=subtab52&menu=search&ri=1&source=~!horizon&term=Watercolorists+--+Australia.&index=PSUBJ |title=The Australian Watercolour Institute / Peter Pinson, Jean Campbell and Peter Laverty ; foreword by Hendrik Kolenberg. |last=Pinson |first=Peter |year=2006 |work=bunbury.wa.gov.au |publisher=Phillip Mathews Book Publishers |accessdate=21 March 2010 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
