 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061202031831/http://www.amandacraig.com/pages/journalism/interviews/malorie_blackman.htm 
 |archivedate=2 December 2006 
 |df= 
}}</ref> She earned an [[Higher National Certificate|HNC]] at [[Thames Polytechnic]] and is a graduate of the [[National Film and Television School]].<ref name="Penguin authors" /><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Malorie Blackman
  | work = 40 artists, 40 days
  | publisher = [[Tate|Tate Online]]
  | year = 2006
  | url = http://www2.tate.org.uk/40artists40days/malorie_blackman.html
  | accessdate = 2007-03-28 }}</ref>

She married Neil in the 1990s and their daughter, Elizabeth Blackman, was born in 1995.<ref name="Craig interview"/> Blackman describing herself: "I'm just Malorie Blackman, a black woman writer."<ref name="Penguin authors" />

==Author==
Blackman's first book was ''Not So Stupid'', a collection of [[horror fiction|horror]] and science fiction stories for young adults, published in November 1990.<ref name="British Library catalogue">{{cite web

  | title = Full Record
  | work = [[British Library]] Integrated Catalogue
  | publisher = The British Library Board
  | url = http://catalogue.bl.uk
  | accessdate = 2007-03-28 }}</ref> Ever since, she has written more than 60 children's books, including novels and short story collections, and also television [[screenplays|scripts]] and a [[theatre|stage play]].<ref name="British Library catalogue" /><ref name="multiple awards (first)">{{cite web
 |title       = Malorie Blackman
 |work        = Contemporary Writers
 |publisher   = [[British Council]]
 |year        = 2007
 |url         = http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth519D6BC107d6922CB1VoU30CEDE6
 |accessdate  = 2007-03-23
 |deadurl     = yes
 |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070411063835/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth519D6BC107d6922CB1VoU30CEDE6
 |archivedate = 11 April 2007
 |df          = dmy-all
}}</ref>

Her work has won over 15 awards.<ref name="multiple awards (first)" /><ref name="multiple awards (second)">{{cite web
  | title = Awards and Prizes
  | work = Kids at Random House
  | publisher = Random House Children's Books
  | url = http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/childrens/grownups/prizes/prizes.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-03-23 }}</ref> Blackman's television scripts include episodes of the long-running children's drama ''[[Byker Grove]]'' as well as television adaptations of her novels ''Whizziwig'' and ''Pig-Heart Boy''.<ref name="multiple awards (first)" /> Her books have been translated into over 15 languages including [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Welsh language|Welsh]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[French language|French]].

Blackman's award-winning ''Noughts & Crosses series'', exploring love, racism and violence, is set in a fictional [[utopian and dystopian fiction|dystopia]]. Explaining her choice of title, in a 2007 interview for the [[BBC]]'s ''Blast'' website, Blackman said that [[tic-tac-toe|noughts and crosses]] is "one of those games that nobody ever plays after [[childhood]], because nobody ever wins".<ref name="BBC Blast interview">{{cite web
  | title = Malorie Blackman – Children and Young People's Writer
  | work = Blast
  | publisher = BBC
  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/blast/about/ask/mblackman_transcript.shtml
  | accessdate = 2007-03-23 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In an interview for ''[[The Times]]'', Blackman said that before writing ''Noughts & Crosses'', her [[protagonist]]s' [[ethnic group|ethnicities]] had never been central to the plots of her books.<ref name="Craig interview"/> She has also said, "I wanted to show black children just getting on with their lives, having adventures, and solving their dilemmas, like the characters in all the books I read as a child."<ref name="Penguin authors" />

Blackman eventually decided to address racism directly.<ref name="Craig interview"/><ref name="BBC Blast interview" /> She reused some details from her own experience, including an occasion when she needed a [[bandage|plaster]] and found they were designed to be inconspicuous only on white people's skin.<ref name="Craig interview"/> ''The Times'' interviewer [[Amanda Craig]] speculated about the delay for the ''Noughts & Crosses'' series to be  published in the [[United States]]: "though there was considerable interest, 9/11 killed off the possibility of publishing any book describing what might drive someone to become a terrorist".<ref name="Craig interview"/> ''Noughts and Crosses'' is now available in the US published under the title ''Black & White'' (Simon & Schuster Publishers, 2005).

''Noughts & Crosses'' was No. 61 on the [[Big Read]] list, a 2003 BBC survey to find "The Nation's Best-Loved Book", with more votes than ''[[A Tale of Two Cities]]'', several [[Terry Pratchett]] novels and ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''.

She was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the 2008 Birthday Honours.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58729 |date=14 June 2008 |page=9 |supp=y}}</ref>

In June 2013, Blackman was announced as the new Children's Laureate, succeeding [[Julia Donaldson]].<ref>Martin Chilton, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/10094538/Malorie-Blackman-is-new-Childrens-Laureate.html "Malorie Blackman is new Children’s Laureate"], ''The Telegraph'', 4 June 2013.</ref><ref>Michelle Pauli, [https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2013/jun/04/malorie-blackman-childrens-laureate "Malorie Blackman is the new children's laureate"], Children's Books, ''The Guardian'', 4 June 2013.</ref>

==Personal life==

Malorie Blackman lives with her husband Neil and daughter Elizabeth in [[Kent]], England. In her free time, she likes to play her piano, compose, play computer games and write poetry.<ref>Preface to ''Tell Me No Lies''.</ref> She is the subject of a biography for children by [[Verna Wilkins]].<ref>Verna Wilkins, [http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/editions/malorie-blackman-biography/9781870516495 ''Malorie Blackman – Author''] Black Stars series, Tamarind/Random House, 2008.</ref>

In March 2014, Blackman joined other prominent authors in supporting the [[Let books be books|Let Books Be Books]] campaign, which seeks to stop children’s books being labelled as 'for girls' or 'for boys'.<ref name="BBC 17 March 2014" >{{cite news |last= Masters |first= Tim |title= Campaign over gender-specific books gains support |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26612080|accessdate=24 November 2014 |website= BBC News |date=17 March 2014}}</ref>

In August 2014, Malorie Blackman was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[Scottish independence referendum, 2014|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland – full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2014-08-07 |accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref>

